The comments above each section represent the files I had these sections on. Since the submission page does not allow multiple files, I have just sticked them together in a single translation unit, and made the helper functions static.

First, I have provided a more robust implementation of the "buffer" struct present in my submission for kadai5. It serves as a generic stack-based memory arena using the default CRT allocator. As the program's complexity grows, it is a good idea to implement a pool memory arena with a free list to properly handle memory frees at any arbitrary address, a limitation that stack-based memory arenas do not have the luxury to afford. Allowing the user to specify a generic memory allocator is also a good idea, as memory allocation should not be the arena's responsibility.

This arena does not take into account memory alignment, which is why "student" has a very peculiar name character count: 244. As is the case for most major compilers, the padding requirements is based on the ordering of the elements inside the struct.

In simpler words, if you remove the name from the struct, you are left with a 64-bit aligned struct with two elements: an i64 (64-bit), an f32 (32-bit),
and extra padding (32-bit), which results in a 16 byte structure.

To fill up the gaps and reach 256 bytes, all you need to do is to subtract 256 from 8 (64 bits) and 4 (32 bits), which results in the 244 bytes left for name.
This alignment is required in older cpus. Modern CPUs can handle byte granularity, however it increases speed, albeit not significantly in this exercise.

Finally, the program should allow up to 256 MiB of student data.